# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: typosquatting-defense
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:typosquatting-defense/brandjacking] While similar to cybersquatting, identity theft or phishing in nature and in possible tactics, brandjacking is usually particular to a politician, celebrity or business and more indirect in its nature.
[src:typosquatting-defense/brandjacking] A brandjacker may attempt to use the reputation of its target for selfish reasons or seek to damage the reputation of its target for hostile, malicious or for political or campaigning reasons.
[src:typosquatting-defense/brandjacking] However, action against the brandjackers and their supporters can actually draw attention to the problem (the Streisand effect).
[src:typosquatting-defense/brandjacking] For example, following Greenpeace's KitKat campaign, Nestlé had the video removed from YouTube, but Greenpeace quickly re-posted it to video-sharing site Vimeo.com and highlighted the attempted censorship using Twitter and other social media.
[src:typosquatting-defense/brandjacking] Attempts by Nestlé to constrain user activity on its Facebook fan page further fanned the controversy.
[src:typosquatting-defense/brandjacking] Brandjacking, which involves the unauthorized use or alteration of a company’s brand identity, is a subject of discussion in both academic and professional research due to its potential to influence public opinion.
[src:typosquatting-defense/brandjacking] Origin, conceptualization and effects of perceived dimensions of truth, mockery and offensiveness* defines brandjacking as a form of anti-commercial parody that changes the original meaning of an advertisement in order to criticize a company or draw attention to perceived concerns about the brand.
[src:typosquatting-defense/brandjacking] One commonly cited concern includes deception.
[src:typosquatting-defense/brandjacking] Some forms of brand hijacking, such as fake accounts, phishing, cybersquatting, and impersonation, may confuse consumers into believing they are interacting with the legitimate company.
[src:typosquatting-defense/brandjacking] According to the study, *Redefining brand hijacking from a non-collaborative brand co-creation perspective* these practices have the potential to damage trust in both the targeted brand and the broader marketplace.
[src:typosquatting-defense/brandjacking] Another ethical issue discussed in research is reputational harm.
[src:typosquatting-defense/brandjacking] Research notes that not all brandjacking is motivated by fraud or personal gain.
[src:typosquatting-defense/brandjacking] For instance, the article *What is brandjacking?
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] In popular terms, "cybersquatting" is the term most frequently used to describe the deliberate, bad faith abusive registration of a domain name in violation of trademark rights.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] However, precisely because of its popular currency, the term has different meanings to different people.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] In the former definition, the cybersquatter may offer to sell the domain to the person or company who owns a trademark contained within the name at an inflated price.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] Similarly, some consider "cyberpiracy" to be interchangeable with "cybersquatting", whereas others consider that the former term relates to violation of copyright in the content of websites, rather than to abusive domain name registrations.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] Because of the various interpretations of the term, World Intellectual Property Organization (WIPO), in a 1999 report, approved by its member states, considered it as the abusive registration of a domain name.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] Since 1999, the World Intellectual Property Organization (WIPO) has provided an administrative process wherein a trademark holder can attempt to claim a squatted site.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] Trademark owners in 2021 filed a record 5,128 cases under the Uniform Domain-Name Dispute-Resolution Policy (UDRP) with World Intellectual Property Organization (WIPO)'s Arbitration and Mediation Center, eclipsing the 2020 level by 22%.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] The surge pushed WIPO cybersquatting cases to almost 56,000 and the total number of domain names covered past the 100,000 mark.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] As a matter of comparison, in 2006, there were 1823 complaints filed with WIPO, which was a 25% increase over the 2005 rate.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] Representing 70% of WIPO's Generic top-level domain (gTLD) cases, .com demonstrated its continuing primacy.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] WIPO UDRP cases in 2021 involved parties from 132 countries.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] The top three business areas were Banking and Finance (13%), Internet and IT (13%), and Biotechnology and Pharmaceuticals (11%).
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] (450), Switzerland (326), and Germany (251) were the top five filing countries.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] In 2007 it was stated that 84% of the claims made since 1999 were decided in the complaining party's favor.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] Some countries have specific laws against cybersquatting beyond the normal rules of trademark law.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] For example, according to the United States federal law known as the Anticybersquatting Consumer Protection Act (ACPA), cybersquatting is registering, trafficking in, or using an Internet domain name with bad faith intent to profit from the goodwill of a trademark belonging to someone else.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] Anticybersquatting Consumer Protection Act in 1999.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] This expansion of the Lanham (Trademark) Act (15 U.S.C.) is intended to provide protection against cybersquatting for individuals as well as owners of distinctive trademarked names.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] Jurisdiction is an issue, as shown in the case involving Kevin Spacey, in which Judge Gary A.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] Feess, of the United States District Court of the Central District of California, ruled that the actor would have to file a complaint in a Canadian court, where the current owner of kevinspacey.com resided.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] Spacey later won the domain through FORUM (formerly known as the National Arbitration Forum).
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] In relation to cybersquatting, the Spanish Supreme Court issued the first sentence on this practice, relating it to the crime of misappropriation (STS 358/2022, of April 7).
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] An unprecedented fact that established the legal fit of this computer crime in Spanish jurisprudence.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] The case revolves around four members of the religious association Alpha Education for Comprehensive Health.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] They created a web page (the Internet domain of which was www.alfatelevision.org) and opened a bank and PayPal account for donations made to the association.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] Sometime later, there were some disagreements between the members of the association and the four defendants who opened a new website, changed the internet domain and the passwords of the accounts, which redirected all the donations from the followers.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] Later, the association dismissed the four members.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] The association's general secretary denounced the four members for a crime of misappropriation, and they were sentenced by the Provincial Court of Guadalajara, understanding that the internet domain was an asset of the association.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] This resolution was appealed to the Supreme Court through an appeal, which was upheld by the court.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] Finally, the Supreme Court acquitted the four accused, understanding that the proven facts did not fit the crime of misappropriation.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] In this sense, it highlights that there are elements that did not concur in this case and that the actions carried out by these individuals (creation of another domain, change of passwords...) occurred prior to their termination and that, therefore, they were in willingness to do it.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] In addition, the sentence reflects cases in which cybersquatting could have criminal relevance.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] In the first place, if the conduct sought to harm the rights of a brand, it could constitute a crime against industrial or intellectual property.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] Secondly, if the intention was to use the domain name in a deceitful way to cause an error in the transfer of assets, the accused could face a crime of fraud.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] Finally, if cybersquatting were used to attack a domain name, the accused would be facing a crime of computer sabotage.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] With the rise of social media websites such as Facebook and Twitter, a new form of cybersquatting involves registering trademark-protected brands or names of public figures on popular social media websites.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] Such cases may be referred to as "username squatting".
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] On June 5, 2009, Tony La Russa, the manager of the St.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] Louis Cardinals, filed a complaint against Twitter, accusing Twitter of cybersquatting.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] The dispute centered on a Twitter profile that used La Russa's name, had a picture of La Russa, and had a headline that said "Hey there!
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] Tony La Russa is now using Twitter." The profile encouraged users to "join today to start receiving Tony La Russa's updates." According to La Russa, the status updates were vulgar and derogatory.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] La Russa argued that the author of the profile intended, in bad faith, to divert Internet traffic away from La Russa's website and make a profit from the injury to La Russa's mark.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] On June 26, 2009, La Russa filed a notice of voluntary dismissal after the parties settled the case.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] Social networking websites have attempted to curb cybersquatting, making cybersquatting a violation of their terms of service.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] An account may be guilty of impersonation if it confuses or misleads others; "accounts with the clear intent to confuse or mislead may be permanently suspended." Twitter's standard for defining parody is whether a reasonable person would be aware that the fake profile is a joke.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] Soon after the La Russa suit was filed, X took another step to prevent "identity confusion" caused by squatting by unveiling Twitter verification.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] Usernames stamped with the "verified account" insignia is intended to indicate that the accounts are real and authentic.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] Facebook reserves the right to reclaim usernames on the website if they infringe on a trademark.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] Trademark owners are responsible for reporting any trademark infringement on a username infringement form Facebook provides.
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] Furthermore, Facebook usernames require "mobile phone authentication".
[src:typosquatting-defense/cybersquatting] In order to obtain a username, the individual needs to verify the account by phone.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] In information theory, linguistics, and computer science, the **Levenshtein distance** is a string metric for measuring the difference between two sequences.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] The Levenshtein distance between two words is the minimum number of single-character edits (insertions, deletions or substitutions) required to change one word into the other.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] It is named after Soviet mathematician Vladimir Levenshtein, who defined the metric in 1965.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] Levenshtein distance may also be referred to as *edit distance*, although that term may also denote a larger family of distance metrics.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] It is closely related to pairwise string alignments.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] where the $\operatorname {tail}$ of some string x is a string of all but the first character of x (i.e. $\operatorname {tail} (x_{0}x_{1}\dots x_{n})=x_{1}x_{2}\dots x_{n}$ ), and $\operatorname {head} (x)$ is the first character of x (i.e. $\operatorname {head} (x_{0}x_{1}\dots x_{n})=x_{0}$ ).
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] Either the notation $x[n]$ or $x_{n}$ is used to refer to the n th character of the string x , counting from 0, thus $\operatorname {head} (x)=x_{0}=x[0]$ .
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] The first element in the minimum corresponds to deletion (from a to b ), the second to insertion and the third to replacement.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] This definition corresponds directly to the naive recursive implementation.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] 3. sittin → sittin**g** (insertion of "g" at the end).
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] The Levenshtein distance has several simple upper and lower bounds.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] An example where the Levenshtein distance between two strings of the same length is strictly less than the Hamming distance is given by the pair "flaw" and "lawn".
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] Here the Levenshtein distance equals 2 (delete "f" from the front; insert "n" at the end).
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] In approximate string matching, the objective is to find matches for short strings in many longer texts, in situations where a small number of differences is to be expected.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] The short strings could come from a dictionary, for instance.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] Here, one of the strings is typically short, while the other is arbitrarily long.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] This has a wide range of applications, for instance, spell checkers, correction systems for optical character recognition, and software to assist natural-language translation based on translation memory.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] The Levenshtein distance can also be computed between two longer strings, but the cost to compute it, which is roughly proportional to the product of the two string lengths, makes this impractical.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] Thus, when used to aid in fuzzy string searching in applications such as record linkage, the compared strings are usually short to help improve speed of comparisons.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] In linguistics, the Levenshtein distance is used as a metric to quantify the linguistic distance, or how different two languages are from one another.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] It is related to mutual intelligibility: the higher the linguistic distance, the lower the mutual intelligibility, and the lower the linguistic distance, the higher the mutual intelligibility.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] The Levenshtein distance can be used to quantify the performance of listeners during speech-identification tests, for various applications such as speech audiometry.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] In this context, Levenshtein distances are calculated to quantify the distance between the stimuli that were presented to the listener and the sequence of phonemes that were identified.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] The cost associated with phoneme substitutions can either be fixed or depend on the number of phonological features that differ between the two substituted phonemes.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] In bioinformatics, the Levenshtein distance and similar algorithms measure the difference between biological sequences, such as those of DNA and protein.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] The edits in the algorithm correspond to genetic mutations: an insertion, deletion, or substitution of a nucleotide (in DNA) or an amino acid (in protein).
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] A lower distance between two sequences can indicate a closer evolutionary or functional relationship.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] There are other popular measures of edit distance, which are calculated using a different set of allowable edit operations.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] Edit distance is usually defined as a parameterizable metric calculated with a specific set of allowed edit operations, and each operation is assigned a cost (possibly infinite).
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] This is further generalized by DNA sequence alignment algorithms such as the Smith–Waterman algorithm, which make an operation's cost depend on where it is applied.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] This implementation is very inefficient because it recomputes the Levenshtein distance of the same substrings many times.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] A more efficient method would never repeat the same distance calculation.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] For example, the Levenshtein distance of all possible suffixes might be stored in an array M , where $M[i][j]$ is the distance between the last i characters of string `s` and the last j characters of string `t`.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] The table is easy to construct one row at a time starting with row 0.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] When the entire table has been built, the desired distance is in the table in the last row and column, representing the distance between all of the characters in `s` and all the characters in `t`.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] This section uses 1-based strings rather than 0-based strings.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] If *m* is a matrix, $m[i,j]$ is the *i*th row and the *j*th column of the matrix, with the first row having index 0 and the first column having index 0.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] This algorithm, an example of bottom-up dynamic programming, is discussed, with variants, in the 1974 article *The String-to-string correction problem* by Robert A.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] The invariant maintained throughout the algorithm is that we can transform the initial segment `s[1..i]` into `t[1..j]` using a minimum of `d[i, j]` operations.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] At the end, the bottom-right element of the array contains the answer.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] It turns out that only two rows of the table – the previous row and the current row being calculated – are needed for the construction, if one does not want to reconstruct the edited input strings.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] Hirschberg's algorithm combines this method with divide and conquer.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] It can compute the optimal edit sequence, and not just the edit distance, in the same asymptotic time and space bounds.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] Levenshtein automata efficiently determine whether a string has an edit distance lower than a given constant from a given string.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] where *ε* > 0 is a free parameter to be tuned, in time *O*(*n*1 + *ε*)..
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] Ten years later, researchers discovered an algorithm with the same running time but an approximation factor of f(1/*ε*), for some function f depending only on *ε* .
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] It has been shown that the Levenshtein distance of two strings of length n cannot be computed in time *O*(*n*2 − *ε*) for any ε greater than zero unless the strong exponential time hypothesis is false.
[src:typosquatting-defense/levenshtein-distance] Another (unconditional) lower bound on the complexity of this problem is $\Omega (mn)$ in a model where the only query on symbols of the strings is comparison of two symbols.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] A **package manager**, or **package management system**, is software that supports installing, upgrading, configuring, and removing software for the host system in a consistent manner.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] A package manager deals with *packages*, distributions of software and data in archive files.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Packages contain metadata, such as the software's name, description of its purpose, version number, vendor, checksum (usually a cryptographic hash function), and a list of dependencies necessary for the software to run properly.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Upon installation, metadata is stored in a local package database.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Package managers typically maintain a database of software dependencies and version information to prevent software mismatches and missing prerequisites.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] They work closely with software repositories, binary repository managers, and app stores.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Package managers are designed to eliminate the need for manual installs and updates.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] This can be particularly useful for large enterprises whose operating systems (OSes) typically consist of hundreds or even tens of thousands of distinct packages.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] An early package manager was SMIT (and its backend install) from IBM AIX.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] SMIT was introduced with AIX 3.0 in 1989.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Package managers like dpkg have existed as early as 1994.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Early package managers, from around 1994, had no automatic dependency resolution but could already simplify the process of adding and removing software from a running system.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] By around 1995, beginning with CPAN, package managers began handling package repository downloads, and dependency resolution and installation as needed, making it easier to install, uninstall and update software.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] A software package is an archive file containing a computer program as well as necessary metadata for its deployment.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] The program may be in source code that has to be compiled and built first.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Package metadata include the software's description, version number, and dependencies.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Package managers are charged with the task of finding, installing, maintaining or uninstalling packages upon the user's command.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Computer systems that rely on dynamic library linking, instead of static library linking, share executable libraries of machine instructions across packages and applications.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] In these systems, conflicting relationships between different packages requiring different versions of libraries results in a situation called *dependency hell*.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] On Microsoft Windows systems, this is also called *DLL hell* when working with dynamically-linked libraries.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Modern package managers have mostly solved these problems by allowing parallel installation of multiple library versions (e.g.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] OPENSTEP's *Framework* system), a dependency of any kind (e.g.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] *slots* in Gentoo Portage), and even packages compiled with different compiler versions (e.g. dynamic libraries built by the Glasgow Haskell Compiler, where a stable ABI does not exist), in order to enable other packages to specify which version they are linked or installed against.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] System administrators may install and maintain software using tools other than package managers.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] For example, a local administrator may download unpackaged source code, compile it, and install it.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] This may cause the local system to fall out of synchronization with the package manager's database.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] The local administrator will be required to take additional measures, such as manually managing some dependencies or integrating the changes into the package manager.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] There are tools to ensure that locally-compiled packages are integrated with the package management.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Upgrades of configuration files may be particularly troublesome.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Since package managers, at least on Unix systems, originated as extensions of file archivers, they can usually only overwrite or retain configuration files, rather than apply rules to them.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] There are exceptions to this that usually apply to kernel configuration (which, if broken, will render the computer unusable after a restart).
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Problems can be caused if the configuration file format changes; for instance, if the old file does not explicitly disable new options that should be disabled.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Some package managers, such as Debian's dpkg, allow configuration during installation.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] In other situations, packages are installed with the default configuration, which is then overwritten, for example in headless installations to a large number of computers.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] This kind of pre-configured installation is also supported by dpkg.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] To give users more control over the software they allow to be installed on their systems, and sometimes due to legal or convenience reasons on the distributors' side, packages are often downloaded from software repositories.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Many package managers can be configured to never upgrade certain packages, or to upgrade them only when critical vulnerabilities or instabilities are found in the previous version, as defined by the packager of the software.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] This process is called *upgrade suppression*, or *version pinning*.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Some of the more advanced package management features offer *cascading package removal*, in which all packages that depend on the target package and all packages that only it depends on are also removed.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Although commands are specific to each package manager, they are translatable to a large extent, as most package managers offer similar functions.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] The Arch Linux wiki offers an extensive overview of commands.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Linux distributions oriented to binary packages rely heavily on package management systems as their primary means of managing and maintaining software.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Mobile operating systems such as Android (Linux-based) and iOS (Unix-based) rely almost exclusively on their respective vendors' app stores and thus use their own dedicated package management systems.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] A package manager is often called an *install manager*, which can lead to a confusion between package managers and installers.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Most software configuration management systems treat building software and deploying software as separate, independent steps.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] A build automation utility typically takes human-readable source code files already on a computer, and automates the process of converting them into an executable package on the same or a remote computer.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Later, a package manager typically running on another computer downloads the pre-built executable and installs it.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] A few tools, such as Maak and A-A-P, are designed to handle both building and deployment, and can be used as either build automation utilities, package managers, or both.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] App stores can also be considered application-level package managers (without the ability to install all levels of programs).
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Unlike traditional package managers, app stores are designed to enable payment for the software itself (instead of for software development), and may only offer monolithic packages with no dependencies or dependency resolution.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] They are usually limited in their management functionality, due to focusing on ease-of-use over power or emergence, and are common in commercial operating systems and smart devices.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Package managers also often have only human-reviewed code.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Many app stores, such as Google Play and Apple's App Store, mainly screen apps using automated tools only; malware can pass these tests by detecting when the app is being tested, and delaying malicious activity.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] There are exceptions: the npm package database, for instance, relies entirely on post-publication review of its code, while the Debian package database has an extensive human review process before any package goes into the main database.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] The XZ Utils backdoor used years of trust-building to insert a backdoor, which was nonetheless caught while in the testing database.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Also known as binary repository manager, it is a software tool designed to optimize the download and storage of binary files, artifacts and packages used and produced in the software development process.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] These package managers aim to standardize the way enterprises treat all package types.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] They give users the ability to apply security and compliance metrics across all artifact types.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Universal package managers have been referred to as being at the center of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Each package manager relies on the format and metadata of the packages in its repository.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] That is, package managers need groups of files to be bundled along with appropriate metadata, such as dependencies.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Often, a core set of utilities manages the basic installation from these packages and multiple package managers use these utilities to provide additional functionality.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] For example, yum relies on rpm as a backend.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Yum extends the functionality of rpm by adding features such as simple configuration for maintaining a network of systems.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] As another example, the Synaptic Package Manager provides a graphical user interface by using the Advanced Packaging Tool (apt) library, which in turn relies on dpkg for core functionality.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Alien is a program that converts between different Linux package formats, supporting conversion between Linux Standard Base (LSB) compliant .rpm packages, .deb, Stampede (.slp), Solaris (.pkg) and Slackware (.tgz, .txz, .tbz, .tlz) packages.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] For mobile operating systems, Google Play uses the Android application package (APK) package format while Microsoft Store uses the APPX and XAP formats.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Both Google Play and Microsoft Store have eponymous package managers.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] By the nature of free and open-source software (FOSS), packages under similar and compatible licenses are available on a number of operating systems.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] These packages can be combined and distributed using configurable packaging systems to handle many permutations of software and manage version-specific dependencies and conflicts.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Some managers of FOSS packages are released as FOSS themselves.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] The ability to continuously upgrade third-party software is typically added by adding the URL of the corresponding repository to the package management's configuration file.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Besides system-level application managers, there are add-on package managers for operating systems with limited capabilities and for programming languages in which developers need the latest libraries.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Unlike system-level package managers, application-level package managers focus on a small part of the software system.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] They typically reside within a directory tree that is not maintained by the system-level manager, such as c:\cygwin or /opt/sw.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] This may not be the case for managers that deal with programming libraries, leading to possible conflicts, as both managers may claim to own a file and may break upgrades.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] Ian Murdock commented that package management is "the single biggest advancement Linux has brought to the industry", that it blurs the boundaries between operating systems and applications, and that it makes it "easier to push new innovations [...] into the marketplace and [...] evolve the OS".
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] There is also a conference for package manager developers known as PackagingCon.
[src:typosquatting-defense/package-manager] It was established in 2021 with the aim to understand different approaches to package management.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] A **supply chain attack** is a cyber-attack that seeks to damage an organization by targeting less secure elements in the supply chain.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] A supply chain attack can occur in any industry, from the financial sector, oil industry, to a government sector.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] A supply chain attack can happen in software or hardware.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Cybercriminals typically tamper with the manufacturing or distribution of a product by installing malware or hardware-based spying components.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Symantec's 2019 Internet Security Threat Report states that supply chain attacks increased by 78 percent in 2018.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] A supply chain is a system of activities involved in handling, distributing, manufacturing, and processing goods in order to move resources from a vendor into the hands of the final consumer.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] A supply chain is a complex network of interconnected players governed by supply and demand.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Alternatively, the term can be used to describe attacks exploiting the software supply chain, in which an apparently low-level or unimportant software component used by other software can be used to inject malicious code into the larger software that depends on the component.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] In a more general sense, a supply chain attack may not necessarily involve electronics.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] In 2010 when burglars gained access to the pharmaceutical giant Eli Lilly's supply warehouse, by drilling a hole in the roof and loading $80 million worth of prescription drugs into a truck, they could also have been said to carry out a supply chain attack.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] However, this article will discuss cyber attacks on physical supply networks that rely on technology; hence, a supply chain attack is a method used by cyber-criminals.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Generally, supply chain attacks on information systems begin with an advanced persistent threat (APT) that determines a member of the supply network with the weakest cyber security in order to affect the target organization.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Hackers don't usually directly target a larger entity, such as the United States Government, but instead target the entity's software.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The third-party software is often less protected, leading to an easier target.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] According to an investigation produced by Verizon Enterprise, 92% of the cyber security incidents analyzed in their survey occurred among small firms.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Supply chain networks are considered to be particularly vulnerable due to their multiple interconnected components.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] APTs can often gain access to sensitive information by physically tampering with the production of the product.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Poorly managed supply chain management systems can become significant hazards for cyber attacks, which can lead to a loss of sensitive customer information, disruption of the manufacturing process, and could damage a company's reputation.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Wired reported a connecting thread in recent software supply chain attacks, as of 3 May 2019.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] These have been surmised to have spread from infected, pirated, popular compilers posted on pirate websites.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] That is, corrupted versions of Apple's Xcode and Microsoft Visual Studio.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] At the end of 2013, Target, a US retailer, was hit by one of the largest data breaches in the history of the retail industry.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Between 27 November and 15 December 2013, Target's American brick-and-mortar stores experienced a data hack.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Around 40 million customers' credit and debit cards became susceptible to fraud after malware was introduced into the POS system in over 1,800 stores.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The data breach of Target's customer information saw a direct impact on the company's profit, which fell 46 percent in the fourth quarter of 2013.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Six months prior the company began installing a $1.6 million cyber security system.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Target had a team of security specialists to monitor its computers constantly.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Nonetheless, the supply chain attack circumvented these security measures.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] It is believed that cyber criminals infiltrated a third party supplier to gain access to Target's main data network.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Although not officially confirmed, investigation officials suspect that the hackers first broke into Target's network on 15 November 2013 using passcode credentials stolen from Fazio Mechanical Services, a Pennsylvania-based provider of HVAC systems.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Ninety lawsuits have been filed against Target by customers for carelessness and compensatory damages.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Target spent around $61 million responding to the breach, according to its fourth-quarter report to investors.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Stuxnet is a computer worm that is widely believed to be a joint U.S.-Israeli cyber operation, though neither government has officially confirmed involvement.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The worm specifically targets industrial control systems, particularly those that automate electromechanical processes, such as factory machinery and nuclear enrichment equipment.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Stuxnet was designed to manipulate programmable logic controllers (PLCs), disrupting industrial equipment by issuing unauthorized commands while simultaneously feeding falsified operations data to monitoring systems to conceal its activity.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Stuxnet is widely believed to have been developed to disrupt Iran's enriched uranium programs.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Kevin Hogan, Senior Director of Security Response at Symantec, stated that most infections occurred in Iran.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Analysts suggest that its primary target was the Natanz uranium enrichment facility.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Stuxnet was initially introduced into Iran's Natanz facility via infected USB flash drives, requiring physical access to the target network.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] According to reports, engineers or maintenance workers, either knowingly or unknowingly, facilitated its entry into the plant.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Once inside, the worm spread autonomously, exploiting multiple zero-day vulnerabilities in Windows systems to propagate across networked machines running Siemens industrial control software.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] In recent years malware known as Suceful, Plotus, Tyupkin and GreenDispenser have affected automated teller machines globally, especially in Russia and Ukraine.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] GreenDispenser specifically gives attackers the ability to walk up to an infected ATM system and remove its cash vault.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] When installed, GreenDispenser may display an 'out of service' message on the ATM, but attackers with the right access credentials can drain the ATM's cash vault and remove the malware from the system using an untraceable delete process.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The other types of malware usually behave in a similar fashion, capturing magnetic stripe data from the machine's memory storage and instructing the machines to withdraw cash.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The attacks require a person with insider access, such as an ATM technician or anyone else with a key to the machine, to place the malware on the ATM.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The Tyupkin malware active in March 2014 on more than 50 ATMs at banking institutions in Eastern Europe, is believed to have also spread at the time to the U.S., India, and China.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The malware affects ATMs from major manufacturers running Microsoft Windows 32-bit operating systems.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The malware displays information on how much money is available in every machine and allows an attacker to withdraw 40 notes from the selected cassette of each ATM.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] In June 2017, the financial software M.E.Doc, widely used in Ukraine, was identified by security researchers as a likely initial vector for the spread of the NotPetya malware.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Security researchers, including those from Microsoft, indicated that NotPetya infections may have originated from a compromised update issued through M.E.Doc.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Some analysts described this as a supply chain attack, though the exact method of compromise was not definitively identified.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The software's developers denied the claim but later deleted their statement and stated that they were cooperating with investigators.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] NotPetya was initially identified as ransomware because it encrypted hard drives and displayed a ransom demand in bitcoin.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] However, the email account used to provide decryption keys was shut down, leaving victims without a way to recover their files.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Unlike WannaCry, NotPetya had no built-in kill switch, making it harder to stop.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The attack affected multiple industries in Ukraine, including banks, an airport, the Kyiv Metro, pharmaceutical companies, and Chernobyl's radiation detection systems.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] It also spread globally, impacting organizations in Russia, the United Kingdom, India, and the United States.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] NotPetya spread using EternalBlue, a vulnerability originally developed by the U.S.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] National Security Agency (NSA) and later leaked.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] EternalBlue had previously been used in the WannaCry cyberattack in May 2017.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] This exploit enabled NotPetya to spread through the Windows Server Message Block (SMB) protocol.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The malware also used PsExec and the Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI) to spread within networks.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Due to these exploits, once a device on a network was infected, the malware could rapidly spread to other connected systems.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Ukrainian police stated that M.E.Doc employees could face criminal liability for negligence, citing repeated warnings from antivirus firms about security vulnerabilities in the company's cybersecurity infrastructure.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The head of Ukraine's CyberPolice, Colonel Serhiy Demydiuk, alleged that M.E.Doc had been repeatedly warned by security firms about weaknesses in its systems but failed to act, stating, "They knew about it." Authorities later reported that M.E.Doc cooperated with investigators.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] From August 21 until September 5, 2018 British Airways was under attack.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The British Airways website payment section contained a code that harvested customer payment data.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The injected code was written specifically to route credit card information to a domain baways.com, which could erroneously be thought to belong to British Airways.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Magecart is the entity believed to be behind the attack.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Magecart is a name attributed to multiple hacker groups that use skimming practices in order to steal customer information through online payment processes.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Approximately 380,000 customers had their personal and financial data compromised as a result of the attack.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] British Airways later reported in October, 2018 that an additional 185,000 customers may have had their personal information stolen as well.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The 2020 SolarWinds cyberattack was linked to a supply chain compromise targeting the IT infrastructure company SolarWinds, which provided software used by multiple U.S. federal institutions, including networks within the National Nuclear Security Administration (NNSA).
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Russian hackers compromised Orion, a widely used network management software developed by SolarWinds, by injecting malicious code into software updates.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] This allowed them to gain unauthorized access to numerous organizations, including multiple U.S. government agencies that relied on Orion for IT monitoring and management.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Department of Homeland Security issued Emergency Directive 21-01, "*Mitigate SolarWinds Orion Code Compromise",* requiring affected federal agencies to disconnect compromised Windows host OS instances from their enterprise domain and rebuild those hosts using trusted sources.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] These compromised systems had been running SolarWinds Orion.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] In December 2020, FireEye identified a cyber breach involving the SolarWinds Orion software, which had been compromised prior to its discovery.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Microsoft was among the organizations affected, detecting and removing malicious files linked to the breach.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Microsoft has since collaborated with FireEye as part of an ongoing investigation into the incident.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The cyberattack targeted supply chain software used across various industries, including government, consulting, technology, telecommunications, and extractive sectors in North America, Europe, Asia and the Middle East.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] None of the Microsoft repositories contained production credentials.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The repositories were secured in December, and those attacks ceased in January.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] However, in March 2021 more than 20,000 US organizations were compromised through a back door that was installed via flaws in Exchange Server.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The affected organizations use self-hosted e-mail (on-site rather than cloud-based) such as credit unions, town governments, and small businesses.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The flaws were patched on 2 March 2021, but by 5 March 2021 only 10% of the compromised organizations had implemented the patch; the back door remains open.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The US officials are attempting to notify the affected organizations which are smaller than the organizations that were affected in December 2020.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Microsoft has updated its Indicators of Compromise tool and has released emergency mitigation measures for its Exchange Server flaws.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The attacks on SolarWinds and Microsoft software are currently thought to be independent, as of March 2021.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The Indicators of Compromise tool allows customers to scan their Exchange Server log files for compromise.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] At least 10 attacking groups are using the Exchange Server flaws.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Web shells can remain on a patched server; this still allows cyberattacks based on the affected servers.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] As of 12 March 2021 exploit attempts are doubling every few hours, according to Check Point Research, some in the name of security researchers themselves.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] By 14 April 2021 the FBI had completed a covert cyber operation to remove the web shells from afflicted servers and was informing the servers' owners of what had been done.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] In May 2021 Microsoft identified 3000 malicious emails to 150 organizations in 24 countries, that were launched by a group that Microsoft has denoted 'Nobelium'.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Many of those emails were blocked before delivery.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] 'Nobelium' gained access to a Constant Contact "email marketing account used by the US Agency for International Development (USAID)".
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Security researchers assert that 'Nobelium' crafts spear-phishing email messages which get clicked on by unsuspecting users; the links then direct installation of malicious 'Nobelium' code to infect the users' systems, making them subject to ransom, espionage, disinformation, etc.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The US government has identified 'Nobelium' as stemming from Russia's Federal Security Service.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] By July 2021 the US government is expected to name the initiator of the Exchange Server attacks: "China's Ministry of State Security has been using criminal contract hackers".
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] In September 2021 the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) enforcement staff have requested that any companies which have downloaded any compromised SolarWinds updates, voluntarily turn over data to the SEC if they have installed the compromised updates on their servers.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] In July 2022 SessionManager, a malicious module hosted by IIS (installed by default on Exchange Servers), was discovered to have infected Exchange Servers since March 2021; SessionManager searches memory for passwords, and downloads new modules, to hijack the server.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Mandiant, a security firm, has shown that nation-state-sponsored groups, once they have gained access to corporate clouds, can now exploit Security assertion markup language (SAML), to gain federated authentication to Active Directory and similar services, at will.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Once the attackers gain access, they are able to infiltrate any information or assets belonging to the organization.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] This is because this technique allows attackers to pose as any member of the targeted organization.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] These attacks are progressively becoming more desirable to malicious actors as companies and agencies continue to move assets to cloud services.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] In 2020, SolarWinds was subject to what is described as the first documented Golden SAML attack, often referred to as "Solorigate".
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] A malicious actor infected the source code of a software update with a backdoor code made to look legitimate.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Customers began installing the faulty update to their systems, ultimately affecting over 18,000 individuals globally.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The attack affected a number of United States government agencies and private sector agencies as well.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] In May 2021, a ransomware attack on Colonial Pipeline forced a temporary shutdown of a major fuel distribution network, disrupting the supply of gasoline, diesel, and jet fuel to the U.S.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The Biden administration invoked emergency powers to prevent shortages, while experts described the incident as the worst-ever cyberattack on U.S. infrastructure.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The attack, attributed to the Russian-linked cybercriminal group DarkSide, raised concerns about vulnerabilities in critical energy systems, as fuel traders sought alternative supply routes and fears of price spikes emerged.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] On June 16, 2021, President Biden stated to President Putin that cyberattacks on 16 critical infrastructure sectors were off-limits and said that the U.S. would respond to future cyber threats.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The 16 critical infrastructure sectors, as designated by the U.S.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency (CISA), include energy, food and agriculture, emergency services, healthcare, and other essential industries such as financial services, communications, and transportation systems.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] On 2 July 2021, about 60 managed service providers (MSPs) and their customers became victims of a ransomware attack perpetrated by the REvil group, causing downtime for over 1,000 companies.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] REvil carried out the attack by exploiting a vulnerability in VSA (Virtual System Administrator), a remote monitoring and management software package developed by Kaseya.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] This was a form of supply chain attack on a software supply chain.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] REvil demanded about 70 million USD in Bitcoin as a ransom.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] On 23 July 2021, Kaseya announced that it had received a universal decryptor tool from a "trusted third party", and it helped customers restore their data.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Two suspects were identified and one sentenced.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] In March 2023, the voice and video chat app 3CX Phone System was thought to have been subject to a supply chain attack due to detection of malicious activity on the software.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The app is used in a wide variety of industries from food to automotive and an attack has the potential to impact hundreds of thousands of users worldwide.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The malware infects the host device through the installation process, acting as a Trojan horse virus spread through both Mac OS and Microsoft installers.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] They employed an infostealer through a malicious payload that connected to a C2 server controlled by the threat actor.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The attack utilized the Gopuram backdoor, originally discovered by the Russian cybersecurity company Kaspersky in 2020.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The use of this backdoor suggested that the attack was executed by the North Korean cybercrime group known as Lazarus due to their use of this same backdoor in a 2020 attack against a South Asian cryptocurrency company.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The Gopuram backdoor has been utilized in other past attacks against cryptocurrency agencies, which Lazarus has been known to target.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] In July 2023, Chinese state-sponsored hackers targeted the United States Department of State, hacking several government employees' Microsoft email accounts, which gave them access to classified information.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] They stole information from about 60,000 emails from several Department of State employees.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Department of State officials have stated that the information stolen includes "victims' travel itineraries and diplomatic deliberations".
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] If used in a malicious manner, this information could be used to monitor important government officials and track United States communications that are meant to be confidential.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The Department of State hack occurred due to vulnerabilities in Microsoft Exchange Server, classifying it as a supply-chain attack.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] In March 2024, a backdoor in xz/liblzma in XZ Utils was suspected, with malicious code known to be in version 5.6.0 and 5.6.1.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] While the exploit remained dormant unless a specific third-party patch of the SSH server is used, under the right circumstances this interference could potentially enable a malicious actor to break sshd authentication and gain unauthorized access to the entire system remotely.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The list of affected Linux distributions includes Debian unstable, Fedora Rawhide, Kali Linux, and OpenSUSE Tumbleweed.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Most Linux distributions that followed a stable release update model were not affected, since they were carrying older versions of xz.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Arch Linux issued an advisory for users to update immediately, although it also noted that Arch's OpenSSH package does not include the common third-party patch necessary for the backdoor.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] FreeBSD is not affected by this attack, as all supported FreeBSD releases include versions of xz that predate the affected releases and the attack targets Linux's glibc.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] On October 31, 2024, cybersecurity researchers from several security firms such as Phylum, Socket, and Checkmarx detected an attack on users of the open-source Node Package Manager (NPM) library.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Unidentified attackers published more than 287 packages in an attempt to trick users of the platform into downloading malicious code.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The attack used a technique called typosquatting, which copies the names of legitimate packages closely, tricking unsuspecting developers into accidentally downloading the wrong one.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] For the package Fetch-mock-jest, the attacker rearranged the order of the words and misspelled the word fetch creating the name "jest-fet-mock".
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Based on the kind of packages mimicked, researchers believe this attack widely targeted software developers using NPM.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Packages targeted are mostly mock HTTP requests and cryptocurrency-related, including Puppeteer, Bignum.js, and Fetch-mock-jest, which are mainly used in development environments.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Phylum researchers noted that these typosquatted packages seemed normal at first glance, but upon closer inspection, they contained obfuscated code that could not be understood.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] After de-obfuscating the code, researchers found that after the malicious package is mistakenly downloaded it automatically runs a script that interacts with an Ethereum smart contract to retrieve the IP addresses of the command and control server (C2) used by the attackers.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The script then identifies the operating system used by the victim machine and downloads compatible malware from the IP address it received from the contract.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] This malware maintains persistent communication with the attacker's C2 server, periodically leaking the user's system information such as the operating system version, GPU, CPU, the amount of memory on the machine, and username.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Checkmarkx researcher Yahud Gelb explains that if researchers attempt to take down a C2 server at a specific IP address, the attacker can just update the Ethereum contract so that it returns a different address.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] When describing the mechanism behind the contract he wrote: "Think of a smart contract on the Ethereum blockchain as a public bulletin board – anyone can read what's posted, but only the owner has the ability to update it".
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] This complicates the issue because the malware can always query the smart contract to update the stored address of the C2 server in case the current one has been taken down by authorities.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Researchers worried that several companies' software development supply chains can be put at risk when attackers typosquat them.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] They elaborate that the untraceable nature of the attack combined with its precisely engineered methods of persistence only adds to the looming threat.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Furthermore, company employees usually have elevated system privileges and access to CI/CD pipelines when using development environments, further endangering the company's and their customer's data.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] They warned that developers who use npm packages like the ones above at any stage of the software development lifecycle must take caution and implement robust dependency scanning before performing any installations.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] There is little to no information on the attackers' identity or their motive.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] However, researchers did find error messages written in Russian within the de-obfuscated code of the malicious packages, but they speculate that this could be a misdirect set up by the real culprits trying to throw off any suspicions.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] In 2025, the popular text editor Notepad++ was subjected to a sophisticated supply chain attack when threat actors compromised the application's update infrastructure at the hosting provider level.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The attack, which began in June 2025 and continued through December 2025, involved the interception and redirection of update traffic from the official notepad-plus-plus.org domain to attacker-controlled servers.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] According to the Notepad++ maintainer, the shared hosting server was fully compromised until September 2, 2025, after which attackers maintained access to internal service credentials until December 2, 2025, allowing them to continue redirecting update traffic.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Kaspersky researchers identified three primary execution chains used between July and October 2025, with attackers constantly changing command-and-control server addresses, downloaders, and final payloads to evade detection.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Security firm Rapid7 attributed the campaign to the Lotus Blossom group (also known as Violet Typhoon or APT31), linking the attacks to infrastructure and tactics previously observed in campaigns targeting cryptocurrency companies and critical infrastructure.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] On January 20, 2026, the eScan antivirus software, developed by Indian cybersecurity firm MicroWorld Technologies, was compromised in a supply chain attack when threat actors breached one of the company's regional update servers and deployed malware to customer systems.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The incident lasted approximately one hour before being detected by security researchers at Morphisec and Kaspersky.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The attack primarily affected users in South Asia, including India, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, and the Philippines.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Attackers replaced the legitimate Reload.exe component of eScan with a malicious executable that disabled future antivirus updates and downloaded additional payloads from command-and-control servers.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] This marked the second breach of eScan's infrastructure, following a 2024 incident where North Korean state-sponsored group Kimsuky exploited the same update mechanism to deploy backdoors and cryptocurrency miners.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] No attribution has been made for the 2026 attack.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] On 12 May 2021, Executive Order 14028 (the EO), *Improving the nation's cybersecurity*, tasked NIST as well as other US government agencies with enhancing the cybersecurity of the United States.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The Comprehensive National Cybersecurity Initiative and the Cyberspace Policy Review passed by the Bush and Obama administrations respectively, direct U.S. federal funding for development of multi-pronged approaches for global supply chain risk management.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] According to Adrian Davis of the Technology Innovation Management Review, securing organizations from supply chain attacks begins with building cyber-resilient systems.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Supply chain resilience is, according to supply chain risk management expert Donal Walters, "the ability of the supply chain to cope with unexpected disturbances" and one of its characteristics is a company-wide recognition of where the supply chain is most susceptible to infiltration.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Supply chain management plays a crucial role in creating effective supply chain resilience.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] In March 2015, under the Conservative and Liberal democratic government coalition, the UK Department for Business outlined new efforts to protect SMEs from cyber attacks, which included measures to improve supply chain resilience.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The UK government has produced the Cyber Essentials Scheme, which trains firms for good practices to protect their supply chain and overall cyber security.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] In 2025, a study by the Austrian Chamber of Commerce (WKO) and AV-Comparatives identified what cybersecurity firms should do to assure their customers about supply chain security.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] This includes disclosing a software bill of materials, maintaining transparent data storage practices, providing detailed incident reports, and offering facilities where customers can inspect source codes and updates for the cybersecurity product.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Only 3 of the 14 vendors examined provided such assurances.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] Supply chain attacks have prompted regulatory bodies to address third-party risk management requirements.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] The Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency (CISA) issued Binding Operational Directive 22-01, requiring federal agencies to remediate known exploited vulnerabilities within specified timeframes.
[src:typosquatting-defense/supply-chain-attack] NIST Special Publication 800-161 *Cybersecurity Supply Chain Risk Management Practices* provides a framework for organizations to identify, assess, and mitigate supply chain risks throughout the system development life cycle.
[src:typosquatting-defense/typosquatting] Once on the typosquatter's site, the user may also be tricked into thinking that they are actually on the real site through the use of copied or similar logos, website layouts, or content.
[src:typosquatting-defense/typosquatting] Spam emails sometimes make use of typosquatting URLs to trick users into visiting malicious sites that look like a given bank's site, for instance.
[src:typosquatting-defense/typosquatting] Many companies, including Verizon, Lufthansa, and Lego, have gained reputations for aggressively chasing down typosquatted names.
[src:typosquatting-defense/typosquatting] Lego, for example, has spent roughly US$500,000 on taking 309 cases through UDRP proceedings.
[src:typosquatting-defense/typosquatting] Celebrities have also pursued their domain names.
[src:typosquatting-defense/typosquatting] Prominent examples include basketball player Dirk Nowitzki's UDRP of DirkSwish.com and actress Eva Longoria's UDRP of EvaLongoria.org.
[src:typosquatting-defense/typosquatting] Later, the URL was redirected to google.com; a 2018 check revealed it to redirect users to adware pages, and a 2020 attempt to access the site through a private DNS resolver hosted by AdGuard resulted in the page being identified as malware and blocked for the user's security.
[src:typosquatting-defense/typosquatting] By mid-2022, it had been turned into a political blog.
[src:typosquatting-defense/typosquatting] However, as of July 2026, goggle.com is no longer operational.
[src:typosquatting-defense/typosquatting] In February 2026, researchers at Have I Been Squatted, working with Ctrl-Alt-Intel, reported a phishing operation called Diesel Vortex that targeted freight and logistics organizations in the United States and Europe.
[src:typosquatting-defense/typosquatting] The campaign used lookalike domains and phishing pages impersonating logistics services, and was reported to have stolen more than 1,600 unique credentials from logistics platforms.
[src:typosquatting-defense/typosquatting] Another example of corporate typosquatting is yuube.com, targeting YouTube users by programming that URL to redirect to a malicious website or page that asks users to add a malware "security check extension".
[src:typosquatting-defense/typosquatting] Similarly, www.airfrance.com has been typosquatted by www.arifrance.com, diverting users to a website peddling discount travel (although it now redirects to a warning from Air France about malware).
[src:typosquatting-defense/typosquatting] Other examples are equifacks.com (Equifax.com), experianne.com (Experian.com), and tramsonion.com (TransUnion.com); these three typosquatted sites were registered by comedian John Oliver for his show *Last Week Tonight*.
[src:typosquatting-defense/typosquatting] Over 550 typosquats related to the 2020 U.S. presidential election were detected in 2019.
[src:typosquatting-defense/typosquatting] The Magniber ransomware is being distributed in a typosquatting method that exploits typos made when entering domains, targeting mainly Chrome and Edge users.
[src:typosquatting-defense/typosquatting] A 2024 peer-reviewed study provides the first large-scale measurement of typosquatting in blockchain-based naming systems, such as Ethereum Name Service, Unstoppable Domains, and ADAHandles.
[src:typosquatting-defense/typosquatting] The researchers observed thousands of cryptocurrency transactions mistakenly sent to squatting addresses, with targets including both popular domain names and identities linked to social media accounts.
[src:typosquatting-defense/typosquatting] In the United States, the 1999 Anticybersquatting Consumer Protection Act (ACPA) contains a clause (Section 3(a), amending 15 USC 1117 to include sub-section (d)(2)(B)(ii)) aimed at combatting typosquatting.
[src:typosquatting-defense/typosquatting] On April 17, 2006, evangelist Jerry Falwell failed to get the U.S Supreme Court to review a decision allowing Christopher Lamparello to use www.fallwell.com.
[src:typosquatting-defense/typosquatting] Relying on a plausible misspelling of Falwell's name, Lamparello's gripe site presents misdirected visitors with scriptural references that are intended to counter the fundamentalist preacher's scathing rebukes against homosexuality.
[src:typosquatting-defense/typosquatting] Under the Uniform Domain-Name Dispute-Resolution Policy (UDRP), trademark holders can file a case at the World Intellectual Property Organization (WIPO) against typosquatters (as with cybersquatters in general).
[src:typosquatting-defense/typosquatting] The complainant has to show that the registered domain name is identical or confusingly similar to their trademark, that the registrant has no legitimate interest in the domain name, and that the domain name is being used in bad faith.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] The objective of the cheat sheet is to provide a proposal of approach regarding the handling of vulnerable third-party dependencies when they are detected, and this, depending on different situation.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Proposals mentioned in this cheat sheet are not silver-bullet (recipes that work in all situations) yet can be used as a foundation and adapted to your context.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Most of the projects use third-party dependencies to delegate handling of different kind of operations, *e.g.* generation of document in a specific format, HTTP communications, data parsing of a specific format, etc.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] It's a good approach because it allows the development team to focus on the real application code supporting the expected business feature.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] The dependency brings forth an expected downside where the security posture of the real application is now resting on it.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] It's highly recommended to perform automated analysis of the dependencies from the birth of the project.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Indeed, if this task is added at the middle or end of the project, it can imply a huge amount of work to handle all the issues identified and that will in turn impose a huge burden on the development team and might to blocking the advancement of the project at hand.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] In the rest of the cheat sheet, when we refer to *development team* then we assume that the team contains a member with the required application security skills or can refer to someone in the company having these kind of skills to analyse the vulnerability impacting the dependency.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] It's important to keep in mind the different ways in which a security issue is handled after its discovery.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Here, the vulnerability is always referenced in the CVE global database used, generally, by the detection tools as one of the several input sources used.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] See a description here, into the section named **Computers** about **Computer Security**.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] The researcher decides to release all the information including exploitation code/method on services like Full Disclosure mailing list, Exploit-DB.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Here a CVE is not always created then the vulnerability is not always in the CVE global database causing the detection tools to be potentially blind about unless the tools use other input sources.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] When a security issue is detected, it's possible to decide to accept the risk represented by the security issue.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] However, this decision must be taken by the Chief Risk Officer (fallback possible to Chief Information Security Officer) of the company based on technical feedback from the development team that have analyzed the issue (see the *Cases* section) as well as the CVEs CVSS score indicators.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] When a security issue is detected, the development team can meet one of the situations (named *Case* in the rest of the cheat sheet) presented in the sub sections below.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If the vulnerably impact a transitive dependency then the action will be taken on the direct dependency of the project because acting on a transitive dependency often impact the stability of the application.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Acting on a on a transitive dependency require the development team to fully understand the complete relation/communication/usage from the project first level dependency until the dependency impacted by the security vulnerability, this task is very time consuming.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Patched version of the component has been released by the provider.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Set of automated unit or integration or functional or security tests exist for the features of the application using the impacted dependency allowing to validate that the feature is operational.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Update the version of the dependency in the project on a testing environment.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Provider informs the team that it will take a while to fix the issue and, so, a patched version will not be available before months.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If a workaround is provided, it should be applied and validated on the testing environment, and thereafter deployed to production.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If the provider has given the team a list of the impacted functions, protective code must wrap the calls to these functions to ensure that the input and the output data is safe.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Moreover, security devices, such as the Web Application Firewall (WAF), can handle such issues by protecting the internal applications through parameter validation and by generating detection rules for those specific libraries.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Yet, in this cheat sheet, the focus is set on the application level in order to patch the vulnerability as close as possible to the source.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If the provider has provided nothing about the vulnerability, Case 3 can be applied skipping the *step 2* of this case.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] We assume here that, at least, the CVE has been provided.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If the provider has provided the team with the exploitation code, and the team made a security wrapper around the vulnerable library/code, execute the exploitation code in order to ensure that the library is now secure and doesn't affect the application.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If you have a set of automated unit or integration or functional or security tests that exist for the application, run them to verify that the protection code added does not impact the stability of the application.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Add a comment in the project *README* explaining that the issue (specify the related CVE) is handled during the waiting time of a patched version because the detection tool will continue to raise an alert on this dependency.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Provider informs the team that they cannot fix the issue, so no patched version will be released at all (applies also if provider does not want to fix the issue or does not answer at all).
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] In this case the only information given to the development team is the CVE.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Nothing specific because here we are in a *patch yourself* condition.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] In all cases, here, we need to handle the vulnerability right now.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] As we know the vulnerable dependency, we know where it is used in the application (if it's a transitive dependency then we can identify the first level dependency using it using the IDE built-in feature or the dependency management system used (Maven, Gradle, NuGet, npm, etc.).
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Note that IDE is also used to identify the calls to the dependency.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Identifying calls to this dependency is fine but it is the first step.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] The team still lacks information on what kind of patching needs to be performed.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] To obtain these information, the team uses the CVE content to know which kind of vulnerability affects the dependency.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] The `description` property provides the answer: SQL injection, Remote Code Execution, Cross-Site Scripting, Cross-Site Request Forgery, etc.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] After identifying the above 2 points, the team is aware of the type of patching that needs to be taken (Case 2 with the protective code) and where to add it.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] The team has an application using the Jackson API in a version exposed to the CVE-2016-3720.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Based on these information, the team determines that the necessary patching will be to add a pre-validation of any XML data passed to the Jakson API to prevent XML external entity (XXE) vulnerability.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If possible, create a unit test that mimics the vulnerability in order to ensure that the patch is effective and have a way to continuously ensure that the patch is in place during the evolution of the project.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If you have a set of automated unit or integration or functional or security tests that exists for the application then run them to verify that the patch does not impact the stability of the application.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Provider collaborates with you after being notified of the vulnerability.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Inform the provider about the vulnerability by sharing the post with them.
[src:typosquatting-defense/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] This section lists several tools that can used to analyze the dependencies used by a project in order to detect the vulnerabilities.
